{
  "id": "019d2ef8-d08b-70b0-81e0-f54c0afc77ee",
  "content": "## Tier-Aware Retrieval Scoring (Issue #22, PR #35)\n\nImplemented tier_weight multiplier in the retrieval scoring path. Applied after cosine similarity in both VectorRetriever and GraphExpandRetriever.\n\n### Tier Weights\n- Hot = 1.0 (full score)\n- Warm = 0.7 (deprioritized)\n- Cold = 0.3 (heavily penalized)\n- Forgotten = 0.0 (excluded entirely from results)\n\n### Key Design Decisions\n- **Unified tier weighting in caller**: `merge_cold_results` does NOT apply tier_weight — the caller (VectorRetriever/GraphExpandRetriever) applies it uniformly to all results. This prevents double-application bugs.\n- **Hot-only fast path**: When all entries are Hot (common case), skip filter/map/re-sort entirely. Uses `any()` short-circuit check.\n- **Forgotten exclusion**: Forgotten entries are filtered out before tier weighting, not scored to 0.0. In GraphExpandRetriever, Forgotten entries are also excluded from graph neighbor expansion.\n- **Graph reinforcement is tier-agnostic**: Reinforcement bonuses from graph edges are NOT multiplied by tier_weight. This is intentional — graph connectivity reflects structural importance independent of recency-based tier.\n- **`pub(crate) const fn tier_weight(tier: Tier) -> f32`**: Takes Tier by value (Copy type), inline hint, crate-internal visibility.\n- **`sort_unstable_by`**: Used instead of `sort_by` for score ordering (no stability requirement for float scores).\n\n### Test Coverage\n9 tier-related tests including:\n- Exact score ratio verification (warm_score / hot_score ≈ 0.7)\n- All-Forgotten scope returns empty results\n- Cold with high cosine outranks Warm with low cosine\n- GraphExpandRetriever excludes Forgotten entries\n\n### Review Finding: Double-Application Bug Pattern\nWhen a helper function (merge_cold_results) and a caller both apply the same multiplier, cold entries get penalized twice (0.3 * 0.3 = 0.09). Fix: apply tier_weight in exactly one place (the caller's unified pass). This pattern should be watched for in any future scoring multiplier additions.",
